class Solution {
    public void duplicateZeros(int[] arr) {
        int count = 0, n = arr.length;
        for(int num : arr) count += (num == 0) ? 1 : 0;
        int lastIndex = n + count - 1;

        for(int i = n-1; i >= 0 && lastIndex >= 0; i--) {
            if(arr[i] == 0) { // set zeroes and move two places backwards (via lastIndex)
                if(lastIndex < n)
				   arr[lastIndex] = 0;
                if((lastIndex-1) < n && lastIndex > 0)
				   arr[lastIndex-1] = 0;
                lastIndex -= 2;
            } else { // set same value and move one place backwards (via lastIndex)
                if(lastIndex < n)
				   arr[lastIndex] = arr[i];
                lastIndex -= 1;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Idea using an example:
- Consider the array: `[8,4,5,0,0,0,0,7]`
- Consider an **imaginary additional length** next to the array that can accommodate the additional zeroes.
- With that idea in mind, the `lastIndex` will be at `length(arr) + count(zeroes) - 1` (in this case, it would be `lastIndex = 11` for `[8,4,5,0,0,0,0,7..0,0,0,0]`)
- Now loop through backwards with `i` being the last element of **actual** array and update the array with **valid** `lastIndex` value decrements.

