# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need two values whose product can be equal to num*num for any num.
Think of solving using two sum approach. 
Store the counts and solve.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Take two maps. Store the count of each element for both arrays in diff maps.
Now for any number in map1 we iterate all elements of map2 if map1*map1 can be formed by products of two numbers of map2 which means for the element in map2 map1%map2 == 0 and map2 should also contain map1/map2.
Now there will be two cases when `m1*m1 = m2*m2` and `m1*m1 = m2*m3`
For the first case we just take 2 elements out of cnt[m2] using nC2.
For the second case we will have repeated answers as we take `cnt[m2]*cnt[m3]` and then when we reach m3 then we have `cnt[m3]*cnt[m2]` so we store both case in separate variables.
Do the same for map2.
Final answer will be case1 + case2/2

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n*m)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: Two maps for nums1 and nums2
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

