solutions.content:
**Here I am discussing my approach to this problem**
**Approach:**
1. Do a **bfs/dfs** on `grid2 matrix` **similar** to what you did in [Number of Islands](https://leetcode.com/problems/number-of-islands/).
2. For a current island in` grid2`, check for every cell in that island **if they are present in** `grid1`. This will **ensure if this is a sub-island** of `grid1`.
3. Maintain a `flag` and mark it false if you **encounter any cell which is part of island in grid2 and not a part of island in grid1**. 
4. **Increase** the `count` for each island of `grid2`, when `flag` is **true**.
5. **Return** `count`, as this will be the **number of islands** in `grid2` that are considered **sub-islands**.

**Source Code:**
```
class Solution {
    public int countSubIslands(int[][] grid1, int[][] grid2) {
        int m = grid1.length;
        int n = grid1[0].length;
        boolean[][] vis = new boolean[m][n];
        int count = 0;
        int[] dir = {1, 0, -1, 0, 1};

        for(int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
            for(int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
                if(grid2[i][j] == 0 || vis[i][j])
                    continue;

                Queue<int[]> queue = new LinkedList<>();
                boolean flag = true;
                vis[i][j] = true;

                queue.add(new int[] {i, j});

                while(!queue.isEmpty()) {
                    int[] vtx = queue.remove();

                    if(grid1[vtx[0]][vtx[1]] == 0)
                        flag = false;

                    for(int k = 0; k < 4; ++k) {
                        int x = vtx[0] + dir[k];
                        int y = vtx[1] + dir[k + 1];

                        if(x >= 0 && x < m && y >= 0 && y < n && grid2[x][y] == 1 && !vis[x][y]) {
                            vis[x][y] = true;

                            queue.add(new int[] {x, y});
                        }
                    }
                }

                if(flag)
                    ++count;
            }
        }

        return count;
    }
}
```

**Complexity Analysis:**
```
Time Complexity: O(m * n) // m = grid2.length, n = grid2[0].length
Space Complexity: O(m * n) // m = grid2.length, n = grid[0].length
```

**Another optimized approach, thanks to [@coderskater114](https://leetcode.com/coderskater114/)**
We can mark `grid2[x][y] = 0` when visited instead of using extra boolean `vis` array and mark it `true`. 
Below is the solution.

